<p>I have a table named <code>TICKET</code>. Among the columns in ticket are two date fields:</p>  <pre><code>TICKET ---------------------------------------- TICKDATE             | ELSDATE     | ... ---------------------+-------------+---- yyyy-mm-dd hh:mm:ss    yyyy-mm-dd </code></pre>  <p>These two dates should always be the same.</p>  <p>I have a range of dates (from 7/1 to current) where ELSDATE is null. I'm just starting out in sql scripting, and I don't know how to update one column to equal the other. The current script I'm running to update one day at a time is:</p>  <pre><code>update TICKET ELSDATE="yyyy-mm-dd" where date(TICKDATE)="yyyy-mm-dd" </code></pre>  <p>I assume I'd be able to do something like:</p>  <pre><code>update TICKET where ELSDATE="???" date(TICKDATE)&lt;date("2015-09-29") </code></pre>